node.text: J. Cole interview with Angie Martinez

let’s talk about 4 Your Eyez only.

People actually don’t know about the risk J. Cole took by releasing an album like this. Imagine coming off the biggest album of your life in 2014 Forest Hills Drive, an album filled from start to end with bangers. Then, at the peak of your success (at the time) releasing an album that is a complete different direction in 4 Your Eyez Only. 
Believe me when I tell you MOST rappers would’ve chose to keep the ball rolling by releasing another album full of hits like Forest Hills Drive. 
That being said, I think albums that have a theme, and a storyline that follows throughout the whole album is better than an album with songs that have randomly been put together like a playlist. 
Every single one of these songs follow a storyline; and the crazy part of it is that these very same songs can be listened to in any order and still enjoyed because they have double meanings! One that follows the storyline when you really pay attention to the lyrics, and the other being just great songs you can vibe to in general 💫

Photo by J. Cole on August 24, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whether it's fiction or not is unclear, but the entire album seems to be a retelling of McMillan's life to the young daughter named Nina he left behind. Cole explicitly spells this out on the album's final track, when he reveals that McMillan told him to communicate his story to his daughter: " Write my story down and if pass Go play it for my daughter when she ready And so I'm leaving you this record for your eyes only only'.

Photo by J. Cole on August 24, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Although this isn't revealed until the very end, the whole album sets up this theme. The opening track "For Whom The Bell Tolls" is a reference to bells ringing at a funeral. On the second track "Immortal," Cole assumes the perspective of a young man-presumably McMillan-who sells drugs as a means to escape poverty, despite the risks: " Kingpin nigga, put wings on a crack fiend If they want a nigga, they gon' have to send a SWAT team And I'm goin' out like Scarface in his last scene A legend, what that mean-?'.

Photo by J. Cole on August 24, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'On the track "Ville Mentality," Cole includes a spoken interlude from a young girl, presumably McMillan's daughter: " My dad, he died-he got shot cause his friend set him up And didn't go to his funeral-and sometimes when I'm in my room, get mad at my momma when she mean to me And she- And she say, clean up-l say- I get mad, slam my door and go in my room- And then, get mad and dad was here" say, "I wish my'.

Photo by J. Cole on August 24, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'A few of the albums tracks-like "Foldin Clothes" and the two "She's Mine" songs focus on love, fatherhood, and their ability to make a man reconsider his priorities in life. This is a theme that likely applies to Cole's own life, but also fits in with the McMillan narrative. On "She's Mine Pt. 2," Cole his life around: raps about the birth of a child inspiring him to turn " You are now the reason that fight I ain't never did nothing thats right in my whole life'.

Photo by J. Cole on August 24, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'He finally lays everything bare on the album's final song "4 Your Eyez Only," revealing that McMillan's biggest fear is his daughter coming home from school to see he was killed. Tragically, this fear came true: " My worst fear is one day that you come home from school And see your father face while hearing 'bout tragedy on news I got the strangest feeling your daddy gonna lose his life soon And sadly if you're listening now it must mean it's true'.
